Biometric authentication techniques are nowadays widely used to establish identities to improve both security and convenience. However, storing permanent biological characteristics such as fingerprints or faces in the database is risky. In this paper, we design and implement NailKey, a new biometric authentication approach that guarantees the mutability like traditional knowledge-based authentication like passwords, while maintaining the feature of unduplicatablility and usability in biometric authentication. NailKey uses existing capacitive fingerprint sensors to capture features on the edge of sanded fingernails. The inputs are very flat arches or ellipses with different shades. Based on the unique structural characteristics of the features, NailKey uses a tree-based algorithm to align and compare features accurately and efficiently. NailKey shows certain diversity and sustainability in the evaluation, demonstrating the effectiveness and application potential of NailKey.